00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:16.400
All right, given that figure A
is a scaled copy of figure B,

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:18.270
that would also mean that figure B is

00:00:18.270 --> 00:00:20.920
a scaled copy of figure A.

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:23.970
And so we would have a common scale factor

00:00:23.970 --> 00:00:25.910
between corresponding sides.

00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:28.920
So, for example, this
side right over here,

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:30.940
it looks like it's playing the same role

00:00:30.940 --> 00:00:33.140
as this side right over here.

00:00:33.140 --> 00:00:35.090
And so what would be the scale factor

00:00:35.090 --> 00:00:37.230
to go from 10 to 12.5?

00:00:37.230 --> 00:00:41.790
What do I have to multiply
10 by to get 12.5?

00:00:41.790 --> 00:00:45.260
Well, I'm multiplying
it by a scale factor.

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:49.580
I'm using a scale factor of 1.25.

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:52.620
I'm multiplying times 1.25,

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:54.030
or you could also think of it

00:00:54.030 --> 00:00:57.580
as I'm multiplying times 1 1/4,

00:00:57.580 --> 00:01:00.230
either way of expressing the same number.

00:01:00.230 --> 00:01:02.450
Well, if I'm thinking about x,

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:05.540
if I want to know this
length right over here,

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:08.440
corresponding to this side on figure B

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:10.680
would be this side on figure A,

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:12.450
which has length 16.

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:15.930
And so I would use the same scale factor.

00:01:15.930 --> 00:01:19.093
So my scale factor here,
once again, would be 1 1/4.

00:01:20.210 --> 00:01:22.903
So I'll multiply times 1 1/4.

00:01:23.770 --> 00:01:26.820
And 1/4 of 16 is four.

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:30.000
So it's going to be 16
and then another four

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.833
is going to be equal to 20.

00:01:32.833 --> 00:01:37.550
1.25 times 16 is equal
to 20, and we're done.

